**Only closing Futenma can reorient the Alliance to deal with pressing security matters**
**O’Hanlon, Senior Fellow @ Brookings, ’10**
[Michael E. O’Hanlon, Director of Research & Senior Fellow on Foreign Policy @ The Brookings Institution, “Window on Washington / Putting 1 Okinawa air base in perspective,” February 3rd 2010, <span style="text-decoration: none;">[[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/columns/commentary/20100203dy01.htm]]</span>] AP
<span class="CardChar0">For 15 years, the two largest economies on Earth and two of the world's top military powers have spent much of their alliance management time discussing the fate of one airfield, the U.S. Marine Corps' Futenma Air Station on the island of Okinawa. This is a poor preoccupation for the allies given the other, huge issues that confront the two countries--dealing with nuclear North Korea, the rise of China, the global problem of Islamic extremism, wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, and many other matters such as recovery from the global recession and mitigation of the global warming threat. It is time to move beyond it. </span><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Various efforts have been made to propose ways to relocate the base in the past. Of course as we all know, it was to go to another part of the main Okinawa Island, given the current facility's location in the heart of Ginowan City and the associated problems of noise, risk of accident, and interference with local economic development strategies. The arrival of Prime Minister Yukio Hatoyama in office, just as a deal finally seemed to be coming together, and now a mayoral election on Okinawa in the jurisdiction that was to host the new base have thrown the latest monkey wrench into the mix. Hatoyama's reluctance pits him against not only the Liberal Democratic Party, but the Japanese bureaucrats who would implement the deal, and the United States--which has said its entire willingness to relocate half of its marines from Okinawa to Guam is contingent on Hatoyama accepting what other parties saw as a done deal. There are arguments on all sides of this issue. </span><span class="CardChar0">Supporters of the proposal to relocate the base on the island note that it is militarily important, economically helpful to Okinawa, which lacks a strong alternative economy, and diplomatically sound as a reasonable and long-sought compromise to the interests of the United States, Japan in general, and Okinawans in particular. But Hatoyama points to the fact that tiny Okinawa continues to host more than half of all U.S. military forces based in Japan, and that its people have been continually conflicted about this sometimes burdensome presence for decades. Some Okinawans worry about the environmental effects of the proposed new airfield site on local sea life; others seek to minimize their island's future economic dependence on the American military. Along with </span><span style="font-size: 10pt;">George Washington University professor and Japan expert </span><span class="CardChar0">Mike Mochizuki, I have long argued that the Kadena Air Force Base on Okinawa is much more militarily important than Futenma, given its likely role in possible conflicts in Korea, the Taiwan Strait or elsewhere as well as its role as a hub in the American global military base network. Preserving local political support for Kadena is therefore much more impotant than holding onto Futenma or its successor. Our analyses suggest that a modest number of helicopter and fixed-wing flights can be handled at Kadena, moreover, for day-to-day marine operations. Just as we make pragmatic decisions in other parts of the world</span><span style="font-size: 10pt;">, including the broader Middle East and Korea, </span><span class="CardChar0">about when to relocate our forces for the greater good of an alliance, we can factor local sensitivities into this issue as well. Moreover, delays in making a decision on relocation, while frustrating for those working on the problem, do not prevent the United States from ongoing use of Futenma as well as other facilities on Okinawa in the meantime. Provided that the United States could improve its contingency access to other airfields on Okinawa for use in a possible crisis or war, the United States could make do without Futenma or a substitute. </span><span style="font-size: 10pt;">However it makes no sense to keep more than 15,000 marines on Okinawa without a dedicated airfield, so in this event, Japan should follow through on its commitment to help finance a major move of many marines from Okinawa to Guam, including an alternative airfield there. Japan only has to spend 1 percent of its gross domestic product on its military, whereas the United States spends 4 to 5 percent and bears a far higher burden in terms of actual combat operations, in an alliance that suits both their purposes but offers Japan the better bargain at the moment on balance. Using commercial or Japanese military airfields in a crisis or war is allowed under the 1996 and 1997 agreements between Tokyo and Washington governing base use in Japan; prestationing of some supplies and engineering equipment on these other airfields could go a long ways toward mitigating the downsides of any loss of a permanent air station. As such, </span><span class="CardChar0">Prime Minister Hatoyama is right not to feel streamrolled by the arguments of defense professionals and establishment figures that Futenma or its successor are militarily crucial to the future of the alliance. </span><span style="font-size: 10pt;">However, Hatoyama has another challenge--to avoid using the Okinawa issue as a way to show his distance from LDP governments and prove his mettle as a reformer. </span><span class="CardChar0">One must not exaggerate the inconvenience or insult to Okinawans from the existing plan for relocating the airfield, which as noted reflects 15 years of negotiations that attempted to factor Okinawan interests into the proposed solution. And at a time when many Western nations led by the United States--but notably not including Japan--are asking their soldiers to risk their lives on global military operations, it is important not to exaggerate the degree to which the Okinawans are being asked to sacrifice disproportionately. </span><span style="font-size: 10pt;">So what it comes down to is this: Prime Minister Hatoyama, as the sovereign leader of a sovereign state, has every right to rethink previous commitments of his country, just as he already has in replacing Japan's Indian Ocean resupply operations for U.S. Navy ships there with a larger aid package for Afghanistan. But that latter policy suggests the way forward here, too: if Hatoyama is to walk away unilaterally from a deal that others in Japan and the United States have worked hard to create, he needs to do something real, and big, and historic instead. Perhaps it would be best if Japan did a little less to please Americans on the issue of bases and host nation military support--provided that it do more in another way. Providing substantial numbers of Japanese peacekeeping troops for Sudan and Congo, as part of the ongoing U.N. missions in those places, comes to mind as a good example of possible contributions consistent with Japanese political sensibilities and with the proper role of a great power on the world stage. </span><span class="CardChar0">Moving toward a true alliance in this way could do much to not only ease the pain over an Okinawa base disagreement, but transcend it as well, and get what Ambassador Mike Mansfield called "the world's most important bilateral relationship" two decades ago. If Mansfield's words are to remain true, or even partly true, today, we need to lift our sights above bickering over bases and put strategy and the world's real problems back at the center of our alliance. </span>

