The truth cannot be more different from this Japanese belief. U.S. policy-makers have been fearing for decades that Japan will one day announce its intention to terminate the alliance. This is because Japan is the most valuable of America's 58 treaty-bound allies in two ways. First, the United States cannot maintain global preponderance without Japan. Second, in military terms, the alliance with Japan is the most symmetric of America's alliances. The first point is obvious from Japan's unique role as America's power projection platform. U.S. military bases in all other allied countries are forward bases for responding to specific regional threats. For instance, bases in the Republic of Korea (South Korea) are for deterring—and failing that, fighting—a war on the peninsula by deploying forces in response to military threats from North Korea. The immense bases in NATO Europe are also for meeting regional threats, as were those in the Philippines, In contrast. U.S. bases in Japan provide the bulk of support for the Seventh Fleet and the III Marine Expeditionary Force, whose area of responsibility stretches from Hawaii to the Cape of Good Hope—one half of the world! Such a power projection platform is vital for America's maintenance of a position from which it can claim global leadership. Japan meets and surpasses various conditions for a power-projection platform. One is industrial and technological development. Few allies are capable of repairing technology-intensive weapons of the U.S. armed forces. In particular, only Japan can repair the U.S. Navy's Aegis air defense system; it is the only ally deploying the system. Another is economic capacity. In the course of acting as the world's leader, the United States sometimes finds itself in a financial shortfall. The ability to provide billions of dollars on such occasions on short notice is certainly a condition for an ally to lie a power-projection platform. While not discussed often, the public's friendliness toward the United Suites is another important condition. From the U.S. perspective, the Japanese are exceptional on this count, even among allies. There is no anti-American nationalism to speak of; it is difficult to believe that the United States has actually dropped two atomic bombs on Japan. Even when the rape of a schoolgirl in Okinawa by U.S. servicemen in September 1995 inflamed anti-base passions, no Japanese stoned or torched military7 bases or any other American property. Hence, on these terms, Japan is equivalent to the continental United States. The loss of the Japanese archipelago would be as damaging to the security and prosperity of the American people as an invasion of the U.S. homeland. Americans would not have an opportunity to become aware of Japan's true worth, however, until and unless Japan terminates the alliance. The second point, that Japan's burden-sharing is more symmetric than any other U.S. ally, is related to Japan's significance as America's power-projection platform. When Japanese citizens hear the term "military contribution," they define it as the deployment of the Self-Defense Forces (Sl)F) into combat. Many are ashamed that Japan cannot participate in this way, whether as America's ally, as a member of a coalition authorized by the U.N. Security Council, or under LJ.N. command. Deploying the SDF abroad can be an important contribution to international peace. However, the Japanese government defines exercise of the right of collective defense, particularly die SDF s participation in what the government routinely characterizes as activities incorporating the use of force, as unconstitutional. Unless Japan lifts this ban through reinterpretation or formal amendment of the Constitution, it cannot, contribute SDF troops. In fact, neither Japan's Asian neighbors nor the United States itself desires amendment of the Japanese Constitution. They do not relish the prospect of Japanese military independence. The interested states thus expect Japan to make a military contribution other than deployment of the SDF Japan has been doing just that to an immense extent, even though few Japanese have noticed. Even leaving aside the financial contribution worth SI3 billion. Japan's military contribution to the U.N.-led effort to contain Iraq in 1990-1991 was second only to America's in both qualitative and quantitative terms. U.S. Department ot Defense specialists acknowledge this reality. Specifically, at least 80 percent of the fuel and ammunition used by the 560,000 U.S. troops in the Persian Gulf was shipped from facilities in Japan, and approximately 20 percent of U.S. combat power in the theater was deployed from Japan. How was this possible? First, the second and third largest U.S. military fuel storage facilities in the world are in Japan: Tsummi (5.7 million barrels) in the port of Yokohama and Sasebo (5.3 million barrels) in Kyushu. Several of the largest munitions depots of the U.S. armed forces are also in Japan. The Army's depot complex near Hiroshima alone can store 119,000 tons. Those of the Air Force, Navy and the Marine Corps are even larger; the Air Force's munitions facility at Kadena Air Base in Okinawa is the largest of its kind in the world. By comparison, the total munitions stockpile of the Japanese Self-Defense Forces is only 115.000 tons. In addition, combat units of nearly every kind deployed from Japan to the Persian Gulf. USS Blue Ridge, the flagship of the Seventh Fleet, directed all operations bv the Navy and the Marine Corps. USS Midway generated more sor- ties than any other aircraft carrier. Marine Corps aviation and ground units and Air Force units also deployed from Japan. In terms of the long tail of logistics and the teeth of combat power, the role of the U.S. military infrastructure in Japan exceeded even that of the British armed forces, which deployed almost 70,000 troops to the Persian Gulf. This is why military analysts regard Japan's contribution as second only to those of the United States, To say that the maintenance of such a power-projection platform costs money is a gross understatement. Japan is spending more than ¥5.1 trillion in the current fiscal year toward this cost. This expenditure breaks down as ¥640 billion in rent. Japanese labor and construction for U.S. military facilities and areas (which accounts for 70 percent of the costs associated with stationing U.S. troops in Japan), plus ¥4.9 trillion in Japanese defense expenditures, from which the Defense Facilities Administration Agency's expenditures for U.S. military facilities and areas worth Y460 billion should be subtracted. This means that the United States pays only for irreducibly military expenditures such as the payroll for U.S. military personnel. Including Japan's defense expenditures for maintaining the alliance may require an explanation. One example should suffice. At the full peacetime complement, the U.S. Air Force, Navy and the Marine Corps deploy more than 200 fighters and attack aircraft in Japan between them. Yet, not one is tasked with air defense. The security of U.S. military bases in Japan from airborne threats depends on the Air Self-Defense Forces umbrella over all of Japan. The Self-Defense Forces, which share this crowded archipelago with U.S. forces, have a force structure appropriate for a perimeter security force of America's power-projection platform. No country in the littorals of the Pacific and Indian Oceans even begins to approach Japan in meeting conditions for a power-projection platform. One year after Japan notifies the United States of its intention to terminate the alliance, the United States would lose leverage, and with it, most of its capability to project military power over half of the world. Shorn of power-projection capability, the United States would be hard-pressed to remain the world's sole superpower. Despite its colossal economy, diversified nuclear arsenal and qualitative advantage in conventional forces, the United States would be just one among several great powers. America's power differential with respect to China, Russia and other major powers would be much smaller. This has been generally acknowledged by U.S. government policy advisers in semiofficial meetings. Then, by way of reports, I convinced Japanese government leaders of the significance of the Americans' agreement.

