<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **Bandow ’09** [Doug Bandow is the Robert A. Taft Fellow at the American Conservative Defense Alliance. A former special assistant to President Ronald Reagan, 2/24/09 “Balancing Beijing” <span style="background-attachment: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: initial; background-origin: initial; background-position: 100% 50%; background-repeat: no-repeat no-repeat; padding-right: 10px;">[[http://nationalinterest.org/article/balancing-beijing-3021]]</span>, SM]</span>
<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> Yet the United States and Soviet Union spent most of the cold war sparring for influence in the Third World to little meaningful effect. Money was spent and lives were lost, but in the end it didn't much matter who was numero uno in Vientiane, Kinshasa, Luanda or Managua. It matters even less today. As my Cato colleague Ben Friedman puts it, "There is little that China can do in Africa to make it stronger or to damage U.S. interests." If Beijing wishes to invest heavily in places with little geopolitical heft, why should the United States object? Even more important, Washington needs to back away from any kind of arms race with the PRC. The latest Pentagon Joint Operating Environment 2008 ominously declared that while Beijing doesn't "emphasize the future strictly in military terms," the Chinese do calculate "that eventually their growing strength will allow them to dominate Asia and the Western Pacific." The annual Pentagon assessment of PRC military spending appears to show Beijing's conscious effort to build a force capable of deterring American intervention against China in East Asia. As a result, Aaron Friedberg, until recently Vice President Cheney's chief foreign-policy adviser, worries that the balance of power "is beginning to shift in way that, under the wrong set of circumstances, could increase the risk of miscalculation and conflict." Yet the question is, what balance of power? Beijing poses no threat to America's homeland or even Pacific possessions and will not do so for decades, if ever. The United States possesses a far stronger military to start-eleven carrier groups to none, for instance-spends five or more times as much as the PRC on defense (excluding the costs of Afghanistan and Iraq) and is allied with most important industrial states in Asia and Europe. There is no Chinese threat or potential threat to America. At issue is relative influence in East Asia and the security of Washington's friends in that region. Yet the PRC so far has been assertive rather than aggressive and those nations, particularly Japan and South Korea, could do much more individually and collectively for regional security. Washington should not hesitate to sell arms to friendly states, including Taiwan, despite Chinese protests, but should leave them with responsibility for their own defense. Of course, a policy of continued restraint by Beijing will make it far easier for the United States to back away. In any case, there is little that Washington can do, at least at acceptable cost, to maintain U.S. dominance along China's borders, as the PRC-whose economy already ranks number two or three, depending on the measure, in the world-continues to grow. Washington would have to devote an ever larger amount of resources to the military, in the midst of economic crisis, to ensure its ability to overcome far more limited Chinese capabilities. Even then, Beijing is unlikely to forever accept U.S. hegemony. Confrontation if not conflict would be likely. The better option would be to temper America's geopolitical pretensions and accept a more influential PRC in its own region. China will grow in power, irrespective of Washington's wishes. America's chief objective should be to ensure that this rise is peaceful, as Beijing has promised. U.S.-China diplomatic relations passed the thirty-year mark last fall. The relationship has survived great challenges and is likely to face even greater ones in the future. But despite inevitable differences between the two nations, much depends upon strengthening their ties. The twenty-first century will turn out far differently-and positively-if America and the PRC prove willing to accommodate each other's economic and geopolitical ambitions.</span>

<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **Status quo marine presence in Japan signals a strategy of Chinese containment—they are an unnecessary burden**</span>
<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> **Mochizuki ’96** [Mike, Ph.D., Japan-U.S. Relations Chair in Memory of Gaston Sigur at the Elliott School of International Affairs at George Washington University, 3-17-96 “Slow-Motion Crisis; China's Missiles Sent an Urgent Mes-sage: Our Asia Policy Needs Fixing,” The Washington Post]</span>
<span style="font-size: 10pt;"> However, just because the symptoms will recede does not mean the underlying problem will go away. China, put down by the West for two centuries, is cognizant of its growing strength and intends to be recognized for it. It also has territorial disputes with many neighbors besides Taiwan, and a perception that the United States wants to box it in militarily and politically. Similar conditions -- between the established powers of Russia, Britain and France on one side, and a rising Germany on the other -- helped produce World War I. Under these circumstances, the trick is for the United States and allies, most notably Japan, to deter China -- while also reassuring Beijing that we are not picking a fight and that we recognize its rightful place at the table of great powers. Getting this policy right requires attention, creativity and some new ideas. China's action will at least have been well-timed if it gives Clinton and Hashimoto a strong sense of purpose about reinvigorating the alliance. Unfortunately, most members of the U.S. and Japanese foreign policy establishments would rather use the summit to endorse the status quo. They take it as gospel that the United States must maintain about 45,000 U.S. troops in Japan and 100,000 in Asia because otherwise Japan and the rest of the region might slip into angst and insecurity. Clinton's own Pentagon officials recently reaffirmed this conventional wisdom with a major strategic review. But there are risks to sticking with the status quo. Tension in the U.S.-Japan alliance, revealed so starkly on Okinawa last fall after U.S. servicemen raped a 12-year-old Japanese schoolgirl, has been developing ever since the end of the Cold War and could easily worsen. Japanese remain pro-American and in favor of the bilateral security relationship. But substantial and growing majorities believe that U.S. bases and military personnel in their country, essentially still at Cold War levels, should be reduced. True, the Japanese-American alliance weathered tough times in the past, surviving the Vietnam War and other major challenges. But in those days, the nearby Soviet threat helped the allies to say they were sorry and make up. Moreover, past crises often led to changes in the way the alliance worked -- and this one should too. At this point, reinvigorating the alliance could best be accomplished by changing the configuration of U.S. forces in Japan, including a reduction in the number of Marine combat units on Okinawa, while asking Japan to play a more forceful role in handling the fundamental future tasks of the alliance. The United States and Japan should distinguish between their vital interests and their important yet less-than-vital interests in Asia. Defense of the open oceans, sea lanes and existing U.S. allies -- Japan, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, the Philippines and Thailand -- are the chief causes worth fighting for. The United States and Japan should also be prepared to contest an unprovoked Chinese attack on Taiwan or the islands of the South China Sea. But all of these scenarios except war on the Korean peninsula would be addressed chiefly with air and naval forces, not Marines. As for war against North Korea, the chief U.S. responses would involve its ground and air forces already in South Korea, air and naval forces in Japan and reinforcements from the United States. Other potential disputes with China should not be addressed militarily. We should follow another Nixon maxim, announced in his speech on Guam in 1969, that the United States has no long-term interest in fighting land wars in Asia. By committing ourselves to what would be primarily a maritime defense strategy, we would deter China from attacking our fundamental interests in the region without reinforcing its two-century old sense of encirclement and subjugation. If China some day caused military trouble in Indochina or Mongolia or other parts of mainland Asia, Washington and Tokyo could establish collective defense accords with other countries in the region to prevent any further encroachments. But these are matters where hyper-vigilance now is unneeded, and is only likely to make things worse. Taking some Marine combat forces home would greatly lessen the strains on Japan's smallest prefecture, now host to nearly 30,000 of the 45,000 American troops in Japan. For example, at the summit Clinton might agree to bring home one or two battalions out of the five typically there, including several thousand troops. Since there are only enough amphibious ships in Sasebo, Japan, for one battalion to be transported, this decision would hardly affect our rapid-response capabilities in the region. Indeed, Clinton and Hashimoto could even improve those capabilities by basing one or more additional amphibious ships in Japan. (The Marines' remaining 35 or so amphibious ships are at present based in the continental United States.) Japan too should take on new responsibilities. While reaffirming its one-China policy, it should publicly and vocally reinforce the U.S. position that an unprovoked (or lightly provoked) Chinese attack on Taiwan would be grounds for extreme concern and joint action. In the military sphere, it should in the short term pass laws allowing it to provide substantial rear support to U.S. forces in times of crisis or war in the Asia-Pacific region. Those laws might be challenged in court, but Japanese politics today are healthy enough to handle whatever outcome this legal process might generate, including if necessary a national debate over modifying constitutional limits on Japan's military activities in wartime. In the longer term, Japan needs to become more of an equal military partner to the United States. Areas for possible collaboration include expanded roles in peace operations, joint naval patrols with the 7th Fleet, and improved integration of communications systems with U.S. ships and planes to permit rapid sharing of targeting data in the event of war. In these tense times in Asian politics, restructuring the U.S.-Japan alliance would send a properly-mixed message to China -- that the United States is generally uninterested in putting land forces up against China's borders, but that we and our allies will, if necessary, fight to defend our core interests in the region. And, by ensuring or even enhancing the Marines' ability to deploy quickly out of Okinawa, it would hardly give North Korea reason to cheer. Rather than simply forget this year's March madness in the Taiwan Straits, we should get our post-Cold War Asian security relationships in shape to reduce the chance of another crisis.</span>

