<span style="font-size: 10.0pt;">However, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">just because the symptoms will recede does not mean the underlying problem will go away</span></span>. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">China</span></span>, put down by the West for two centuries, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">is cognizant of its growing strength and intends to be recognized for it. It also has territorial disputes with many neighbors besides Taiwan, and a perception that the United States wants to box it in militarily and politically</span></span>. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Similar conditions</span></span> -- between the established powers of Russia, Britain and France on one side, and a rising Germany on the other -- helped <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">produce World War I</span></span>. Under these circumstances, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">the trick is for the United States and allies, most notably Japan, to deter China -- while also reassuring Beijing that we are not picking a fight and that we recognize its rightful place at the table of great powers</span></span>.Getting this policy right requires attention, creativity and some new ideas. China's action will at least have been well-timed if it gives Clinton and Hashimoto a strong sense of purpose about reinvigorating the alliance.Unfortunately, most members of the U.S. and Japanese foreign policy establishments would rather use the summit to endorse the status quo. They take it as gospel that the United States must maintain about 45,000 U.S. troops in Japan and 100,000 in Asia because otherwise Japan and the rest of the region might slip into angst and insecurity. Clinton's own Pentagon officials recently reaffirmed this conventional wisdom with a major strategic review.But <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">there are risks to sticking with the status quo</span></span>. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Tension in the U.S.-Japan alliance, revealed so starkly on Okinawa</span></span> last fall after U.S. servicemen raped a 12-year-old Japanese schoolgirl, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">has been developing ever since the end of the Cold War and could easily worsen</span></span>. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Japanese remain pro-American and in favor of the bilateral security relationship. But substantial and growing majorities believe that U.S. bases and military personnel in their countr</span></span>y, essentially still at Cold War levels, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">should be reduced</span></span>.True, the Japanese-American alliance weathered tough times in the past, surviving the Vietnam War and other major challenges. But in those days, the nearby Soviet threat helped the allies to say they were sorry and make up. Moreover, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">past crises often led to changes in the way the alliance worked -- and this one should too.</span></span>At this point, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">reinvigorating the alliance could best be accomplished by changing the configuration of U.S. forces in Japan, including a reduction in the number of Marine combat units on Okinawa</span></span>, while asking Japan to play a more forceful role in handling the fundamental future tasks of the alliance.The United States and Japan should distinguish between their vital interests and their important yet less-than-vital interests in Asia. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Defense of the open oceans, sea lanes and existing U.S. allies -- Japan, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, the Philippines and Thailand -- are the chief causes worth fighting for</span></span>. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">The United States and Japan should also be prepared to contest an unprovoked Chinese attack on Taiwan or the islands of the South China Sea.</span></span> But <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">all of these scenarios except war on the Korean peninsula would be addressed chiefly with air and naval forces, not Marines. </span></span>As <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">for war against North Korea, the chief U.S. responses would involve its ground and air forces already in South Korea, air and naval forces in Japan and reinforcements from the United States</span></span>.Other <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">potential disputes with China should not be addressed militaril</span></span>y. We should follow another Nixon maxim, announced in his speech on Guam in 1969, that <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">the United States has no long-term interest in fighting land wars in Asia.</span></span> By <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">committing ourselves to what would be primarily a maritime defense strategy, we would deter China from attacking our fundamental interests in the region without reinforcing its two-century old sense of encirclement and subjugation</span></span>.<span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">If China some day caused military trouble</span></span> in Indochina or Mongolia or other parts of mainland Asia, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Washington and Tokyo could establish collective defense accords with other countries in the region to prevent any further encroachments.</span></span> But <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">these are matters where hyper-vigilance now is unneeded</span></span>, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">and is only likely to make things worse.Taking some Marine combat forces home would greatly lessen the strains on Japan's smallest prefecture, now host to nearly 30,000 of the 45,000 American troops in Japan</span></span>. For example, at the summit Clinton might agree to bring home one or two battalions out of the five typically there, including several thousand troops. Since there are only enough amphibious ships in Sasebo, Japan, for one battalion to be transported, this decision would hardly affect our rapid-response capabilities in the region. Indeed, Clinton and Hashimoto could even improve those capabilities by basing one or more additional amphibious ships in Japan. (The Marines' remaining 35 or so amphibious ships are at present based in the continental United States.)Japan too should take on new responsibilities. While reaffirming its one-China policy,<span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;"> it should publicly and vocally reinforce the U.S. position that an unprovoked (or lightly provoked) Chinese attack on Taiwan would be grounds for extreme concern and joint action</span></span>. In the military sphere, it should in the short term pass laws allowing it to provide substantial rear support to U.S. forces in times of crisis or war in the Asia-Pacific region. Those laws might be challenged in court, but Japanese politics today are healthy enough to handle whatever outcome this legal process might generate, including if necessary a national debate over modifying constitutional limits on Japan's military activities in wartime. <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">In the longer term, Japan needs to become more of an equal military partner to the United States.</span></span> Areas for possible collaboration include expanded roles in peace operations, joint naval patrols with the 7th Fleet, and improved integration of communications systems with U.S. ships and planes to permit rapid sharing of targeting data in the event of war.<span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">In these tense times in Asian politics, restructuring the U.S.-Japan alliance would send a properly-mixed message to China -- that the United States is generally uninterested in putting land forces up against China's borders</span></span>, but <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">that we and our allies will, if necessary, fight to defend our core interests in the region</span></span>. And, <span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">by ensuring or even enhancing the Marines' ability to deploy quickly out of Okinawa, it would hardly give North Korea reason to cheer</span></span>.<span class="underline0"><span style="text-decoration: none; text-underline: none;">Rather than simply forget this year's March madness in the Taiwan Straits, we should get our post-Cold War Asian security relationships in shape to reduce the chance of another crisis.</span></span> </span>

